22.body:
Begin by defining your first plugin class. Hereâ€™s an example implementation in Java: public class HelloWorldPlugin extends ProviderPlugin { public HelloWorldPlugin() { super("Hello World", "1.0.0"); } @Override public void onEnable() { getLogger().info("Plugin Hello World enabled"); } @Override public void onCreate(@NotNull UUID id) { } @Override public @NotNull List<Serie> getSeries(@NotNull UUID id) { return List.of( new Serie("temp", "temperature") ); } @Override public @NotNull LinkedList<TimedValue> getSerieData(@NotNull UUID id, @NotNull String serieId, @NotNull Instant start, @NotNull Instant end) { var now = Instant.now(); var list = new LinkedList<TimedValue>(); list.add(new TimedValue(now, 25.0)); list.add(new TimedValue(now.plusSeconds(60), 26.0)); list.add(new TimedValue(now.plusSeconds(120), 27.0)); list.add(new TimedValue(now.plusSeconds(180), 28.0)); return list; } @Override public boolean status(@NotNull UUID id) { return true; }
}
22.breadcrumbs: Native Plugins Â» Hello World Â» Step 1: Define Your First Plugin Class
22.title: Step 1: Define Your First Plugin Class

23.body: onEnable() : Logs a message when the plugin is enabled. onCreate(UUID id) : Reserved for initialization tasks when creating a DataProvider using this plugin. getSeries(UUID id) : Returns a list of series available for the plugin (e.g., temperature). getSerieData(UUID id, String serieId, Instant start, Instant end) : Provides data for a specific series within the given time range. status(UUID id) : Returns the status of the plugin (always true in this example).

32.body:
The signature is built from a string called data , which is created using the Parse function. This function concatenates the fields as follows: func (this *SharedAccessSignature) Parse() string { return fmt.Sprintf("sv=%s&st=%s&se=%s&sp=%v&sr=%s", this.Version, this.CreatedAt, this.ExpireAt, this.Access, this.DataProviderId)
}

} Explanation of Fields series : Array containing details of available series. id : Unique identifier of the series. start and end : Define the time range for the series in ISO 8601 format. Data outside this range will be excluded .

52.body: Generate a valid token header. Make a GET request to {baseUrl}/api/v1/dataprovider/iotclient/syncedseries. Parse the response to retrieve the id and time range (start, end) for each series. Use the retrieved details to manage or add data to the series, ensuring data falls within the specified range. This process ensures efficient synchronization and data management for your series in the DataProvider.
